    <text>
        <body>
            <head>220. Letter From Representative <persName corresp="recCOBvvhJZ0rjkxZ">Donald M.
                    Fraser</persName> to Secretary of State <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Vance</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d220fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Staff Material. Middle East, Subject File, Box 87,
                    Spanish Sahara: 5–12/77. No classification marking. Copies were sent to
                        <persName corresp="rec9EBLnqQPcxRtYr">Christopher</persName>, Young,
                        <persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu">Brzezinski</persName>, Flaten,
                    Richardson, <persName corresp="recSL4LMg1w3nFIv6">Quandt</persName>, and
                        <persName corresp="rec5GEL623QULbMYE">Veliotes</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1977-12-02"
                        >December 2, 1977</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Dear Mr. Secretary:</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>In light of the upcoming visit by King <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh"
                    >Hassan</persName> of <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                >Morocco</placeName>, I recently wrote the President a letter on the question of the
                    <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf">conflict</rs> in
                    <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Sahara</placeName>, urging him to
                discuss with the King the issues of <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3vXdKC3r5GaUzW"
                    >self-determination</rs> in the Sahara and the question of U.S. <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs> to <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>. Although I sent you a copy at
                the time, I am enclosing another one for your information.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d220fn2">Not attached; printed as <ref target="#d219">Document
                    219</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>As a follow-up to this letter, as well as subsequent meetings between the
                subcommittee staff and <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">U.S.
                    government</rs> officials on this subject, I thought I would put in writing some
                specific points and recommendations on <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recrfy3UsY8QMsqLL">U.S. policy</rs> toward <placeName
                    corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Sahara</placeName>.</p>
            <p>United States official policy on <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western
                    Sahara</placeName> remains essentially unchanged from the past:</p>
            <p>—U.S. is neutral in the <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf"
                    >conflict</rs>;</p>
            <p>—U.S. acknowledges administrative control of <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK"
                    >Western Sahara</placeName> by <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi"
                    >Mauritania</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> without acknowledging their claims of sovereignty;</p>
            <pb facs="0555" n="534" xml:id="pg_534"/>
            <p>—The question of exercise of <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3vXdKC3r5GaUzW"
                    >self-determination</rs> is a fair legal question, but the United States does
                not make a judgment on it, as this would prejudice a peaceful resolution of the
                dispute and would negatively affect our <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recsWOnchx3QJo5qE">relations</rs> with <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>, as well as <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi">Mauritania</placeName>;</p>
            <p>—The United States has urged on occasion that those involved in the dispute should,
                in resolving the problems, avail themselves of the international organs as the
                    <orgName corresp="recakWMbLwDF9eCZ8">United Nations</orgName> and the <orgName
                    corresp="reclJ1I8Ix3s26TFu">Organization of African Unity</orgName>.</p>
            <p>In past administrations, this official policy has been used as a facade covering a
                posture of abstaining in actions that would upset our good <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recsWOnchx3QJo5qE">relations</rs> with
                    <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>.</p>
            <p>The present <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">administration</rs>,
                however, has committed itself to actively upholding and promoting international <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2">human rights</rs>, which include the
                right to expression of <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3vXdKC3r5GaUzW"
                    >self-determination</rs>. It therefore seems important that the <rs type="event"
                    corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">United States Government</rs> substantiate its
                official policy toward <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western
                    Sahara</placeName> in the following manner:</p>
            <p>—The United States should begin to make clear, through quiet diplomatic channels, to
                the nations involved—<placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>,
                    <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi">Mauritania</placeName>, <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>—that it intends to more actively
                pursue, bilaterally and through the <orgName corresp="recakWMbLwDF9eCZ8">United
                    Nations</orgName> organs, its public policy, than has been the case in the past;
                that there are important differences in the manner in which the United States has
                carried out this policy in the past and how it will be carried out in the
                future;</p>
            <p>—The United States strongly supports an end to the fighting in the region;</p>
            <p>—The United States supports the idea that participants in the <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf">conflict</rs> work out
                conditions under which the people of <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western
                    Sahara</placeName> can be allowed to determine the status of their political
                future <hi rendition="simple_italic">under international auspices</hi>;</p>
            <p>—The United States should show great interest in the upcoming meeting by the <orgName
                    corresp="reclJ1I8Ix3s26TFu">Organization of African Unity</orgName> that will
                reportedly be held in <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> in
                March of 1978,<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d220fn3">The <gloss target="#t_OAU_1">
                        <orgName corresp="reclJ1I8Ix3s26TFu">OAU</orgName>
                    </gloss> meeting in Cairo was cancelled. At the <gloss target="#t_OAU_1">
                        <orgName corresp="reclJ1I8Ix3s26TFu">OAU</orgName>
                    </gloss> Summit held in Khartoum July 18–22, 1978, regarding the <placeName
                        corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Sahara</placeName>, the <gloss
                        target="#t_OAU_1">
                        <orgName corresp="reclJ1I8Ix3s26TFu">OAU</orgName>
                    </gloss> adopted a resolution to set up an ad hoc committee, known as the
                    Wisemen’s Committee, “to find a solution to this question compatible with <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="rec3vXdKC3r5GaUzW">self-determination</rs>.” See <ref
                        target="#d45fn4">footnote 4, Document 45</ref>.</note> to resolve the
                conflict in this region;</p>
            <p>—The United States should consult with <placeName corresp="recfnWmyxHI2lF8xT"
                    >Spain</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                >France</placeName>, both of which are on record as favoring <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec3vXdKC3r5GaUzW">self-determination</rs> and both of which take the
                position that even the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recCKnWuUvJmnpBze"
                    >Madrid Agreement</rs> has yet to be carried out by <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>, with a view to seeing what
                further can be done to assist in the process of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec3vXdKC3r5GaUzW">self-determination</rs>;</p>
            <pb facs="0556" n="535" xml:id="pg_535"/>
            <p>—The United States should reiterate that U.S. law limits use of its <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs> to internal and collective
                defense, and prohibits such assistance for acts of agression.</p>
            <p>Your consideration to these matters is greatly appreciated.</p>
            <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recCOBvvhJZ0rjkxZ">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Donald M. Fraser</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d220fn4">Printed from a copy that bears this
                        typed signature.</note>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Chairman <lb/> Subcommittee on International
                        Organizations</hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
